Introduction¶

Background¶

In the area of music information retrieval (MIR) different methods are investigated to extract useful information from music data. The importance of this research area has been grown with the rise and availability of digital music and music streaming services [1]. Music genre classification is one of the challenges in MIR. Tzanetakis and Cook (2002) [2] explained that music genres are “categorical labels created by humans”. Automating this process is a challenging task, since the labels are based on subjective human categorization, which suffers from vagueness [3]. In this work we will try to replicate the results of Huang, Serafini and Pugh (2018)[4]. While Huang, Serafini and Pugh (2018) investigated multiple approaches towards the problem of genre classification, we will focus on their most successful attempt. The authors have been able to achieve a 82% accuracy on the training dataset using a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) approach with preprocessed data [4].
Table 1: "Accuracy of predictions by model used." Huang et al. (2018) [4]

Related Work¶

Classical approaches towards the music genre classification problem made use of extracting hand crafted features (timbral texture, rhythmic content, etc.) which were used in combination with classical machine learning approaches like k-nearest neighbors and gaussian mixture models to classify the different genres [2].

In 2013, Humphrey, Bello, and Lecun pointed out, that progress seemed to plateau in the area of content-based music informatics and elaborated, why hand-crafted features for analysis are suboptimal and why deep learning models achieve potentially better results [5]. Since then, different deep learning approaches have been investigated, such as LSTM-classifier [6], Graph-Neural-Networks [7] or hybrid-architectures [8].

Wyse (2017) [9] showed that audio data in the form of a spectrogram can be analysed using convolutional neural networks. CNNs for music genre classification are a widely used method [10, 11]. Most of them use the Mel-Spectrogram feature in order to classify audio.

Mel-Spectrograms project normal spectrograms onto the mel scale. This leads to a visualisation in which low frequency bands are shown very precisely and higher frequency bands are shown in a compressed way [12]. Dong (2018) explained that the human ear functions in a similar fashion with higher precision on the lower frequency band. Furthermore, he was able to show that some CNN filters are similar to the spectrotemporal receptive field from the human auditory system [12].

Dataset¶

For this replication, we take the audio files from the GTZAN [13] dataset. This dataset was published 2002 [3] and is a widely used dataset in the field of music genre classification [14, 15]. It is the same dataset that was also used by the authors Huang, Serafini and Pugh [4]. GTZAN consists of 1000 wav-audio files with each 30 secounds of length, which are sorted by musical genre.

The following code cell will show you the first five samples of our dataset. It contains the name of the file, the corresponding path and the genre. Since the data isn't shuffled yet, the first samples are of the same genre, namely blues in this case.

The sampling rate is equal across all audio files. For our dataset it is 22050.

Compared to other datasets (see table 1) one of its main advantages is that it is a balanced dataset with an equal number of samples per class category. This means that there are 100 files of each genre, as we have 1000 files in total. Accordingly, we can use the regular accuracy metric instead of the balanced accuracy without any problems.
Table 2: "Datasets for MGC, ordered by year of publication, specifying the size of the dataset, the number of classes or labels and the features each dataset provides." Ramírez and Julia Flores (2019) [3]

However, the GTZAN dataset has been reviewed by Sturm (2013) [15], who identified multiple faults and points of critique such as its small size, mislabeling, repetitions or distortions [15]. Nevertheless, it was a widely used dataset (see figure 3) and is still a benchmark dataset in many modern deep learning papers such as: [2,4,7,8,10,12]
Figure 1: "Annual numbers of published works in MGR with experimental components, divided into ones that use and do no use GTZAN." Sturm (2013) p.12 [15]

To achieve a comparable result we used the GTZAN dataset an apply the same preprocessing steps described in the paper we replicate [4] (see preprocessing for detailed information).

Concept¶

Preprocessing¶

In general, we aim to follow the same preprocessing steps as the authors [4].

To do this, we first extract four randomly selected 2-second windows from each audio file. Therefore, we get 400 2-second samples for each genre, that is 4000 samples in total, evenly distributed in terms of genre.

To get the duration of each signal in seconds we need to devide it by the sampling rate:

s = signal

len(s)= length of signal s

sr = sampling rate of s

d = duration in seconds

$\frac{len(s)}{sr} = d$

$\Leftrightarrow len(s) = d * sr$

In [4]:
len_signal = 2 * sampling_rate
print("To receive two-second random clips from our audio signal, we have to look at {} continous entries in our raw numpy signal.".format(len_signal))

To receive two-second random clips from our audio signal, we have to look at 44100 continous entries in our raw numpy signal.

To achieve this we pick one random starting index and make sure it can maximally be at 28 seconds. We then return the signal from that point to the point plus two seconds and do this four times for each audio file.

In [5]:
# get a random starting point in the 30 sec. clip
def get_rand_sample(signal,duration,sr=22050):
    ''' samples a random part of a signal
    
    Parameters:
        signal (np.array): the signal from which a random sample should be drawn
        duration (int): how long the sample should be (in seconds)
    
    returns:
        np.array:  random part of signal of length duration (in seconds)
    
    '''
    len_signal=duration * sr
    rand_index = np.random.randint(len(signal)-len_signal+1,size=1)[0]
    
    return signal[rand_index: rand_index+len_signal]
example = get_rand_sample(signals[np.random.randint(len(signals))],2,sr=sampling_rate)
assert(len(example)/sampling_rate==2.0)
ipd.Audio(example, rate=sampling_rate)
Out[5]:

In the next step, we transform our samples to so-called Mel-Spectrograms. Spectrograms are simply-speaking plots visualizing sound. Mel-Spectrograms are spectrograms that are "mel-scaled", so that the mel-scale is on its y-axis. The mel-scale results from a transformation of the frequency scale, such that it resembles the frequency band that humans can perceive.

Moreover, the authors stated, that they converted the "raw" audio into Mel-Spectograms, but we are sure they refer to the two-seconds random clips and not the 30-seconds clips. We assume this since the resulting spectogram which you will see below for two seconds looks exactly like the one authors showed in their paper. The "raw" 30 seconds Mel-Spectogram looks not like the spectograms in the paper, however, we will investigate these later on.

To get the Mel-Spectogram we use librosas melspectrogram() method.

In terms of parameters the authors said that they chose the following parameters:

"64 mel-bins and a window length of 512 samples with an overlap of 50% between windows. Based on previous academic success with such transformations, we then move to log-scaling using the formula $log(X^2)"$.

Huang, Serafini and Pugh (2018) p.2 [4]

We use the exact same parameters when converting our samples to Mel-Spectrograms. After running the following code cells you will be able to see two versions of a random example of a two-seconds Mel-Spectrogram.

example = get_rand_sample(signals[np.random.randint(len(signals))], 2, sr=sampling_rate)

# fix parameters
N_MELS = 64
SR = sampling_rate
N_FFT = 512 # window length
HOP_LENGTH = N_FFT // 2 # "50% overlap between the windows"

# convert to log decibel
mel_log = lambda x: lb.power_to_db(x**2) 

mel = lb.feature.melspectrogram(example, sr=SR, n_fft=N_FFT, hop_length=HOP_LENGTH, n_mels=N_MELS)

plt.imshow(mel_log(mel))

The first version is the one that the authors [4] use, whereas the second one is another version of a Mel-Spectrogram that could potentially be used for classification.

Compared to each other, you might notice that they look quite similar, even though their colour schemes are very different from each one another and the first spectrogram has an axis compared to the second. However, the frequency pattern in the second spectrogram pictures the same frequency distribution, but is depicted upside down. Still, training and testing with this reversed mapping should not be a feature that could alter the CNN's performance in comparison with using only the first (not inversed) spectrogram. Although, three other different features, namely colour scheme, axis and scale, could have an influence, as they add or reduce information in each sample.

Eventually, we decided to use the first version of spectrograms as input for our model. The reason is that, even if using the second version might improve our results, we want our results to be comparable to the authors', thus the input to our model must be the same.

Model Architecture¶

As already mentioned, the model we use is a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN). As it has many layers and regularizations, we suggest that you take a direct look at our architecture, which you can see in the following code cell.

In general, we try to copy the architecture of [4]. However, we notice that using all layers and especially all dropout-layers, training does not seem to occur (left out layers are commented).

In [10]:
def cnn(input_shape, num_genres):
    inputs = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=input_shape)
    
    # 1st Conv-Pool-layers
    x = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, 
                               kernel_size=(4,4), 
                               activation=tf.keras.activations.relu)(inputs)
    x = tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,4))(x)
    
    # 2nd Conv-Pool-layers
    x = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, 
                               kernel_size=(3,5), 
                               activation=tf.keras.activations.relu,
                               kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.04))(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2))(x)
#     x = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(x) --> this layer was included in Huang et al.'s implementation

    # 3rd Conv-Pool-layers
    x = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, 
                               kernel_size=(2,2), 
                               activation=tf.keras.activations.relu)(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2))(x)
#     x = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(x) --> this layer was included in Huang et al.'s implementation
    
    # Flatten before feeding into dense layers
    x = tf.keras.layers.Flatten()(x)
    
    # Dense layers
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(64,activation=tf.keras.activations.relu, kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.04))(x)
#     x = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5)(x) --> this layer was included in Huang et al.'s implementation
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(32,activation=tf.keras.activations.relu, kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.04))(x)
    
    # output layer
    output = tf.keras.layers.Dense(num_genres, activation=tf.keras.activations.softmax)(x)
    
    cnn_model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=output)
    return cnn_model

Concerning the hyperparameters, we use a batchsize of 32, an adam optimizer and a categorical cross-entropy loss. We train for 30 epochs in total, which takes approximately 5 hours. Additionally, we chose to use a relatively small learning rate of 0.0005 to guarantee convergence.

Training and Testing¶

During training we observed similar overfitting behaviour like the others. Adding L2 Regularization helped decreasing overfitting at the start of the training progress, while the whole training progress takes longer.

Adding dropout-layers like Huang, Serafini and Pugh (2018) resulted in no learning (validation accuracy of ~10%) even after 70 epochs. This overfitting does also indicates that the data might be fitted better with a simpler model.

In terms of overfitting the Huang et al. report that:

"(...) all four of our models struggle with over-fitting. We spent the most time trying to mitigate this issue on the CNN. To do so, we introduced three methods. We played around with a combination of batch normalization, dropout layers, and L2 regularization. We found some difficulty in using this, as allowing the model to over-fit actually increased our accuracy. While we could bring the training accuracy and the test accuracy to within .05 of each other, this would result in poor model performance. Thus we accepted our over-fitting issue."

We share this experience with the authors and also accepted overfitting, since dropout-layers or increasing the regularization leads to no learning at all instead of reducing overfitting.
Figure 2: Loss [4]
Figure 3: Accuracy [4]

One can see how overfitting seems to increase after approximately 12 epochs. We tried handling this issue with no success. Our validation accuracy peaks at the last 2 episodes at around 57% which is much lower than Huang et al.'s with 82% (see table 1). Nevertheless, with further investigation regarding overfitting we are convinced that we could have increased the accuracy even more. Unfortunately, we have been limited by finite computing resources which made proper hyperparameter testing and handling overfitting nearly impossible for us.

Evaluation and Discussion¶

Compared to the results of Huang et al. [4], we observe slightly similar learning pattern. Our model tends to misclassify similar genres e.g. classifies jazz as classical and rock as country (see figure 5). Huang et al. made similar observations (figure 4), though they could not observe as many misclassifications as we can with our model (e.g. classifying blues as jazz). However, they have a much higher accuracy than we have, probably as they had the resources to train for 300 epochs, whereas we could only train for 30 epochs. They achieved about 95% accuracy in their trainingset and 82% accuracy in their testset (see table 1), whereas we only achieved an accuracy of 97% in the traingsset and 57% in the testset. Unfortunately, we do not have any information about the train/test-split size from [4], which limits the comparability of our results with the results of [4]. Nevertheless, as our training accuracy is relatively low compared to [4], we expect that with further training, we can potentially improve our test accuracy.
Figure 4: "Confusion matrix for CNN predictions." Huang, Serafini and Pugh (2018) [4] Figure 5: Our Results

Conclusion¶

To conclude, we have been able to reproduce the results of [4] to some extend. We observed similar training behaviour and similar genre classification patterns. Although our model's performance has not been as good as Huang et al.'s, our results suggest that further training might lead to a better performance that is more similar to Huang et al.'s.
